{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594411"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:47:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15310"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15310"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66000"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8001"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3430"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19456"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22067"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66000"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman has a liver biopsy for a lesion that was picked up incidentally on a CT scan (Image). The specimen shows a well-circumscribed mass composed of normal-appearing hepatocytes arranged in plates two cells thick. The lesion contains a central stellate scar with radiating fibrous septa. There are proliferating bile ductules at the interface between hepatocytes and fibrous regions. No cellular atypia or mitotic figures are present.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cavernous haemangioma","Focal nodular hyperplasia","Hepatic adenoma","Hepatocellular carcinoma","Regenerative nodule"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe histological features described are classic for \u003Cstrong\u003Efocal nodular hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by a central stellate scar with radiating fibrous septa and proliferating bile ductules. This is distinct from \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatic adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E which lacks a central scar and bile ductules. \u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E shows cellular atypia and mitotic figures, which are absent here. \u003Cstrong\u003ERegenerative nodules\u003C/strong\u003E are typically multiple and lack a central scar. \u003Cstrong\u003ECavernous haemangioma\u003C/strong\u003E consists of dilated vascular channels lined by endothelial cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFocal nodular hyperplasia is a benign tumour-like lesion that occurs predominantly in young women and is often associated with oral contraceptive use. It is the second most common benign liver tumour after haemangioma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Focal nodular hyperplasia appears as a well-circumscribed mass with a central stellate scar and radiating fibrous septa.","Focal nodular hyperplasia is the second most common benign liver tumour after haemangioma.","Focal nodular hyperplasia occurs predominantly in young women and is associated with oral contraceptive use."],"references":["Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808","LeGout JD, Bolan CW, Bowman AW, Caserta MP, Chen FK, Cox KL, Sanyal R, Toskich BB, Lewis JT, Alexander LF. Focal Nodular Hyperplasia and Focal Nodular Hyperplasia-like Lesions. Radiographics. 2022 Jul-Aug;42(4):1043-1061. doi: 10.1148/rg.210156. Epub 2022 Jun 10. PMID: 35687520."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15310"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21264"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21264"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/r1el2wVshMNNfVudHA3CKFHWhAcEWH.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/r1el2wVshMNNfVudHA3CKFHWhAcEWH.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":425}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T16:29:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T16:30:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8001"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66000"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"descri